review_text: Thank you for the course. It was great material and I have passed the certification exam. Really appreciate the effort that both of you have done in preparing me.

Great overview of the topics covered in the ML Associate exam. Frank and Stephane make a good tag team covering the theoretical and hands-on perspectives of each feature. I like the quizzes and the practice exam. One suggestion is to have a section that deep dives into sample ML scenarios. This would help provide the big picture that brings everything together.

The course is amazing and cover everything related to the AWS ML Engineer Associate certification. This course help me clear the certification. I reduced the half star as some session we very long and redundant and the ordering of session can be improved.

I took the certification exam yesterday July 27 2025. This course was spot-on for the exam — it covered nearly everything I faced. I followed the videos over two weeks (one-two hour/day), then spent two more weeks practicing with ChatGPT and Grok. Overall I prepared for 2 months. The actual test was a little tougher than the practice questions. May be I should have trained chatGPT/Grok to produce difficult questions. Glad I passed on first attempt. Highly recommend for focused, real-world readiness.

This course is not well-organised, a lot of AWS service was introduced at the end of the course but they use it to explain with other services like AWS cloudWatch with the sagemaker at the beginning and without explain what the service are. It was so confused.
Let’s start with something positive: The course covers all relevant topics. I did not encounter any unexpected questions during the exam, and I passed.

Miss Stephan's teaching style with clarity as most of the course is covered by Frank. The 2 stars are for Stephan. Frank's teaching is abysmal 1/ he just reads the slides 2/most of the important things he talks are not on slide 3/unnecessary images 4/ Extremely confusing arrangement of lectures, all of sudden neural networks concepts come up without explaining the basics. The algorithm lectures are all over the place. It is very difficult for person like me that needs to understand the concept and cannot mug it. Don't bother if you cannot mug up the concepts.

Dear Stephan, Please find someone else to co-author this course again. This guy Frank Kane speaks too fast, doesn't go deeper to the concepts. He has added only a few numbers of Hands-on as he is openly saying that he doesn't have money.! Very poor! I have bought many courses from Stephan, all are excellent, except this one!

Dear Frank, The course content does a good job explaining the fundamental concepts, but the delivery and examples could be made simpler for greater clarity. No offence intended—I've found that Stephane's teaching style makes complex ideas even more approachable. For your future courses, I sincerely suggest spending more time refining your slides and using more straightforward examples to make the concepts even easier to grasp. Thank you for your effort in creating this course. I'm currently going through my first round and plan to take the MLA exam at the end of October. I will provide additional feedback once I've completed the exam attempt.
Stephan's parts are really good, but I didn't like them as much as Frank Kane's parts. This is mainly due to the outdated material and some points that are already depreciated.

This is an excellent course that gave me the confidence to take the AWS Certified Machine Learning Engineer Associate exam. The comprehensive content covers essential concepts including AWS ML services like SageMaker and Bedrock, data preparation, feature engineering, and model deployment strategies. I particularly appreciated the sections on hyperparameter tuning, CI/CD pipelines, and cost optimization techniques. The knowledge is presented clearly and practically, making complex topics easy to understand. Highly recommend this course for anyone preparing for the AWS ML certification or looking to strengthen their machine learning skills on AWS.
A huge thank you to Frank Kane and Stephane Maarek! I’m thrilled to share that I passed the AWS Certified Machine Learning – Associate exam on my first attempt.

In my exam slot, there were a few questions on security, but overall, the course offered a solid overview. I passed the exam with a score of 855.

I have mixed feelings about this course. On one hand, Frank's teaching style is fantastic—he explains concepts in a way that is incredibly easy to grasp, and his enthusiasm has motivated me to dive deeper into AI. The hands-on exercises are also very effective, making the learning experience engaging and practical. However, I find it frustrating when the he references topics or lectures that are not part of this course or haven't been discussed yet. Additionally, the course videos seem to be picked from AWS ML Specialty and Foundations courses, which makes the content feel disjointed and not well-organized. While there are many positives, these issues detract from the overall learning experience.

Good on the AWS side, but some of the more general ML/DL information in section 6 is just flat wrong. For example, in the CNN lecture Frank describes the fully-connected and dropout layers after CNN and pooling layers as being the same as a multi-layer perceptron network. MLPs don't have dropout. Similarly, in the L1 and L2 regularization lecture he describes L1 as "the sum of the weights". It's actually the sum of the absolute value, which the slide correctly shows, but he verbally describes it incorrectly. I would suggest this section be reviewed by someone with more technical familiarity with ML/DL

The instructor did a good job of explaining the various concepts and services available, such as Amazon SageMaker, AWS Glue, and Amazon Rekognition, among others. The course material is extensive and provides a solid foundation for anyone looking to pursue the AWS Certified Machine Learning Associate certification.

I think too much content is recycled from other courses. Stuff from other courses is referenced all the time like "In the last video we did" when it's not the case or "There's no point going into detail for a practicioner level" when this course is preparing for associate.

This course has several issues. First the content is not well organized, its jumps from topic to another without any structure. In addition, the content is cobbled together from other older courses, with information that seems outdated. I suppose my biggest feedback after giving the exam, using this course to prepare, is that this course does not go into the level of depth expected in the exam. Do not rely on this exam, you will need to go much deeper in the content for the exam.
